12.title: 2. Intro to Programming in Python

13.body: Everything you do on the computer has a computer program ‚Äî ‚Äúsoftware‚Äù ‚Äî behind the scenes. We write computer programs to help us solve problems or perform tasks, like editing documents, browsing web pages, sharing images, or chatting with friends.
13.breadcrumbs: Admissions Challenge ¬ª What is a program?
13.title: What is a program?

14.body: Underneath the screens and keyboards, computers are mechanical. They only understand 1s and 0s. But, people don‚Äôt think in 1s and 0s ! When you want something, you use words. So, how do we tell computers what we want them to do, like ‚Äúsend a message‚Äù or ‚Äúshow this webpage‚Äù? We need a translator . Programming languages let us write instructions for computers using words . Those words translate into instructions that the machine understands (1s and 0s). Then, we can type something like ‚Äúsend a message‚Äù, and it‚Äôll get translated into something like 00011101001010001 001010010001001 101000010010100 10001010001010100000 01001010010, which will make the computer send the message.
14.title: Translating for machines

15.body: Programming languages are very picky about what you type in. You can‚Äôt actually type in send a message ‚Äî the programming language wouldn‚Äôt understand! Instead, it would be more like send_message("Hello!") . The program has to be crafted precisely, with lots of attention to detail, so that the programming language knows exactly what you mean. Programming languages only understand a few specific words and symbols , in a few specific combinations . Those words, symbols, and combinations are the vocabulary, grammar and syntax of a programming language ‚Äî and that‚Äôs what you‚Äôll learn in this course!
15.breadcrumbs: Admissions Challenge ¬ª A Very Picky Translator
15.title: A Very Picky Translator

16.body:
Python is a programming language. You can write Python code, and then it will turn into instructions the computer understands and runs. Here‚Äôs a small program that prints out 10 copies of the word ‚ÄúProgramming‚Äù. message = "Programming"
number_of_copies = 10 print(message * number_of_copies) # ProgrammingProgrammingProgrammingProgrammingProgrammingProgrammingProgrammingProgrammingProgrammingProgramming As you can see: It uses words, like message and print and numbers like 10 It uses symbols like = , *, and () The words and symbols are arranged in a particular order
16.title: What is Python?

17.body: Python is a general purpose programming language , which means it‚Äôs a good fit for a wide variety of problems. Python is popular for data science , mathematics , web development , and more. It‚Äôs commonly used for ‚Äúscripting‚Äù - small programs to do specific tasks. Python is a widely recommended language for beginners. The syntax is not as hard to get started with as some other languages, and you can build cool, real-world projects with it.

22.body:
In Python, you can add things together with the + operator. print(10 + 10) # 20
print(10 + 154) # 164
print(12345 + 23456) # 35801 Computers are good at arithmetic ‚Äî they are very fancy calculators. Python can also add text together with +: message = " loves programming"
print("Adesola" + message)
print("Chidi" + message)
print("Ebbe" + message) The program would output: Adesola loves programming Chidi loves programming Ebbe loves programming Click the green ‚ñ∂Ô∏è button to run a program and see the output in the Console box. Note: if the embedded code below doesn‚Äôt work, you can click this link to go directly to the repl: https://replit.com/@kibocurriculum/Adding-with
22.title: 4. Adding with +

23.body:
Python can ask the user to type in a message using input. favorite = input("What is your favorite thing? ")
print("I like " + favorite + " too!") When the program sees input, it prints the message and waits for the user to enter their response. Then, it continues from there. The variable favorite stores the value that the user typed in. If the user typed in playing soccer, then the output would look like: What is your favorite thing? playing soccer I like playing soccer too! When you run this program, be sure to click in the black ‚ÄúConsole‚Äù box to type a response and press Enter. You need to schedule lots of practice time. We love learning to code together. Once the program starts, you‚Äôll work with partners and groups . We want everyone who enrolls in Kibo to be successful.
